Hi, I'm Zeynep

About me

As an UX Researcher and Designer, my goal is to understand ​humans and make an impact on their lives. My background ​in Theology (B.S.) and Education (M.S.) has let me ​understand how emotions, thoughts, stories, subconscious, ​and unconscious biases impact people’s feelings and ​perception of a product or anything. I create useful, beautiful, ​simple, and friendly designs that people love.


Outside of work, I enjoy baking and decorating cakes, hiking, ​spending quality time with my family and friends, and ​swimming.


Let's get in touch if you want to make something that people ​will love.

Case Study 1

How might we design a welcoming Lykkå Village web ​interface to smoothly transition existing Facebook user ​families, attract new users, and foster connections for an ​enhanced local support network?

PROJECT OVERVIEW

Lykkå Village in Montreal connects parents, especially single moms ​and newcomers, partnering with a co-living startup to drive social ​justice and innovation in neighborhoods.


As part of a multidisciplinary team, I redesigned the activity page ​and implemented a user-friendly payment flow within a 4-week ​timeframe.


We were given a few constraints:

  1. The main presentation of activities will be on the interactive ​map.
  2. The primary way to view events will be through the event display ​card.


I conducted qualitative user research methods, I aim to


  • Make the activity and payment process smooth and easy.
  • Craft an interactive map perfectly suited to user needs and ​expectations.
  • Improve event display card clarity, information, and call to action.


Research Setup

  1. Document Analysis

2. Heuristic Analysis

  • I analyzed documents provided by the ​client and discovered reliable ​information for my research and ​decision-making.



  • KEY TAKEAWAYS


    • Users find it challenging to locate the ​combined phone number and email ​address


    • Users value event details, member ​counts, and participant profiles.


    • Free events contributes to platform ​familiarity and cost-effectiveness.


    • Users express concerns about ​security, particularly regarding ​potential spam or irrelevant events.


  • Heuristic Analysis allowed me to ​identify common usability issues. ​The goal is to improve the user’s ​experience and product’s success.



  • KEY TAKEAWAYS


    • I crafted recommendations to ​improve the user experience.


    • I emphasize usability issues and ​presented to the client





3. Competitive Analysis

  • Competitive analysis allowed the ​team to learn from successful ​brands, gather examples for our ​design decisions.



  • KEY TAKEAWAY


    • I incorporated competitor ​insights and user-centric ​features to significantly ​improve the Lykkå platform's ​experience.


Design Process

Step 1 : Sketches

Activities Sketches


After completing my research, I initiate the process of visually ideating ​steps. This approach helps me to further develop and advance my work.



Step 2: Mid-Fi Wireframe Version 1

Updated Design of Activities Main Dashboard version 1

  • I created mid-level wireframes for detailed visuals,
  • got early client feedback, and
  • collaborated with the developer to ensure both visual appeal and ​technical feasibility.
  • After receiving developer feedback, I redesigned the pages and ​conducted tests with six participants.

Design Process

Step 3: Mid-Fi Wireframe Version 2 Interview Key Insights

Updated Design of Activities Main Dashboard version 2

  • To address technical limitations identified by developers, I made the ​following design updates before conducting user interviews:


    • Relocated the toggle button away from the map to improve user ​interaction.
    • Combined the search bar, create event, and ticket sections into a single ​floating button to optimize space and accessibility.

Mid-Fi Wireframe Version 2 Interview Key Insights

  • Misunderstanding of floating button
    • Six participants thought it was only for creating an event, causing ​unclear functionality.
  • Toggle button confusion
    • Initially unclear, participants understood its map view/listview switch ​upon clicking.
  • Lack of clear "register" or "get ticket" button
  • Unclear "join" button purpose
    • Clicking "join" wasn't clear for expressing intent to attend an event.


Design Process

Step 4: Mid-Fi Wireframe Final Version

Final Activities Main Dashboard and Event Display Card View

  • I redesigned the pages to address these issues, resulting in the final version ​of the mid-fi wireframes.
  • Based on the interview results, the most important changes and final ​website updates are:
    • I made the filter section simpler and added a separate section for ​easy access to search, create an event, and a ticket icon—no extra ​clicks needed.
    • I labeled the toggle button "Map View" and "User List View" to ensure ​user understanding.
    • I added a "Register" button with direct access to ticket purchase.
    • I changed the event card display from horizontal to vertical for easier ​element addition and seamless adaptation to the mobile version ​without a full redesign.

See: final mid-fidelity wireframes

Design Process

Step 4: Mid-Fi Wireframe Final Version

When clicked “attend”, the label switches to” going”. When clicking ​on going, it switches back to attend.


Compact event display combines profiles, attendance count ("5+" for ​overflow), and click/scroll for details.

Design Process

Step 4: Mid-Fi Wireframe Final Version

When clicked “attend”, the label switches to” going”. When clicking ​on going, it switches back to attend.


Compact event display combines profiles, attendance count ("5+" for ​overflow), and click/scroll for details.

outcomes & Learning

  • Minimum Viable Product (MVP) design delivered and accepted.
    • At the end of the project, the founders of Lykkå Village embraced the new ​web design and initiated the implementation of the Minimum Viable ​Product (MVP) per design.


  • The Lykkå Village website become a more user-friendly platform.


  • I enjoyed
    • collaboration,
    • a user-centric approach,
    • working around technical constraints,
    • clear user communication,
    • iterative nature of user experience design.


Case Study 2

How might we increase event attendance at ConnectUp, ​fostering stronger community connections and supporting ​individuals in overcoming social anxiety?

PROJECT OVERVIEW

ConnectUp, a social networking startup, is committed to helping individuals ​overcome social anxiety and make new friends by creating a user-friendly social ​experience.


Target user was ages 32 to 55 who recently relocated to a new city.


As a UX researcher and designer for ConnectUp, my primary focus is on ​understanding and solving the issue of poor event attendance. My work is ​scoped to redesign the user experience and corresponding user interface.


We were given a few constraints:

  1. Implementing features like video integration and real-time chat are not an ​option.
  2. Any incentive introduced would need to be cost-effective for the company.


I conducted mixed-methods research to address the following key challenges


  • bridging the gap between event commitments and actual turnout.
  • boosting event attendance while maintaining cost-effectiveness.
  • refining the overall user experience for enhanced event discover.


Research Setup

  1. Surveys and User Interviews
  • To gain deeper insights, I selected five individuals ​from a survey of twenty-six participants for in-depth ​discussions.


  • KEY TAKEAWAYS


    • Incomplete or inconsistent event information.
    • Difficulty finding details like event content, cost, ​location, and registration instructions.
    • Limited event options aligned with user interests ​and locations.
    • Cost considerations and social anxiety.
    • Inclusive and welcoming event environments



2. Empathy Map

An Empathy Map sample for an onsite interview participant.

  • I crafted 5 empathy maps utilizing insights ​from interviews.

Research Setup

3. Personas

I've created the following two personas using Empathy Maps to ensure a focus on real user needs throughout ​the design and development process.

Yi's concerns include the affordability of events, incentives for ​participation, and addressing social barriers to fostering ​friendships

Mahmut's focus is primarily on the efficiency of event discovery ​and planning, as well as addressing the atmosphere at events.

  • I designed a low-fidelity wireframe for testing purposes ​and conducted user interviews with five individuals


  • Key takeaways from the interviews
    • recommend implementing a guest login option and ​login feature,
    • adding age suitability filters,
    • introducing a note-taking feature with suggestions ​for potential improvement."


The goal was

    • visually unite design,
    • ensure user-friendly ​navigation,

outcome & learnings

  • Performed UX research and delivered UI design with prototype.
  • In the ConnectUp project, I delivered the design and prototype enhancing user ​experiences by
      • providing clear event details,
      • introducing perks like early registration,
      • simplifying event discovery and management.
      • simplified ticket purchase,
      • efficient event search to bridge the gap between intentions and participation.


  • Lessons learned include
    • avoiding assumptions about user interactions,
    • prioritizing user needs,
    • making continuous improvements based on user feedback.


  • Enjoyed a user-centric approach and continuous refinement for creating meaningful ​connections.


Case Study 3

How might we make Arya, the Google Docs AI Writing ​Assistant, reduce stress and writing time for non-native ​English speakers?

PROJECT OVERVIEW

Arya AI Writing Assistant is an Extension for Google Docs that ​uses artificial intelligence to enhance and simplify the writing ​process.


Its primary goal is to help non-native English speakers to ​reduce their stress level while writing in English. It achieves this ​goal by reducing the time users spend on writing.


Target user was non-native English speakers who write in ​English.


As a UX Researcher and Designer for ConnectUp, my primary ​focus was researching the challenges non-native English ​speakers face when writing in English, with the aim of creating ​a user-friendly interface.


I conducted mixed- research to help non-native English ​speakers:

  • Feel confident and less stressed when writing.
  • Write faster and easier.
  • Express themselves clearly and accurately.
  • Communicate effectively in emails and chats.



Research Setup

  1. Surveys and User Interviews
  • To gain deeper insights, I selected five individuals from ​a survey of twenty-six participants for in-depth ​discussions.


Difficulties for Non-Native English Speakers: Survey Results


  • KEY TAKEAWAYS USER INTERVIEWS
  • People had problems
    • remembering proper vocabulary,
    • making an introduction,
    • and writing a conclusion.



2. Affinity Map

Affinity Diagram: Non-Native English Speakers' Writing Challenges

  • I created an affinity map to gain a better understanding ​of the breadth of ideas and challenges faced by non-​native English speakers in writing properly.


Research Setup

3. Personas

Perfectionist : Spends too much time writing, especially ​making an introduction and summarizing, in order to look ​professional in all details.


Procrastinator: Loses motivation and postpones writing, ​reducing the pace of writing.


Business person: Wants to maintain a polite tone in their ​writing.


Research Setup

  1. Ideation

2. MVP

Arya AI Writing Assistant ideation Chart

Topic-based intro templates: Get started quickly with ​customizable templates.

Conclusion generator: Wrap up your writing with a strong ​closing.

Missing word/phrase suggestions: Enhance clarity and ​fluency with AI-powered suggestions.

Grammar and vocabulary checks: Ensure accuracy and ​expand your language skills.


Arya AI Writing Assistant MVP

Step 1: User Flow

Connectup User Flow

  • I started to design a user flow to ensure simplicity and ease of navigation

Step 2: Low Fi Wireframe

Arya Ai Writing Assistant Low-Fi Wireframe

  • I created low fi wireframe and tested with 5 participants
  • KEY TAKEWAYS
    • A clear route back to the homepage.
    • The importance of a clear "back arrow" button for navigating ​back to previous pages.
    • lack of an easy way for users to compare different results.

Design Process

Step 3: Design Inspiration and Style Guide

  • I created a mood board and style guides. These guides include fonts and colors that align with Arya AI Writing Assistant key attributes, such as reliable, efficient

STEP 4: High Fi Wireframe

Design process

After I got feedbacks from usability test on my low fi wireframes, I updated and create a high fidelity wireframes and a clickable prototype, then tested it with users for ​feedback.

  • Based on insightful user interviews on low fi wireframe , I implemented ​the following improvements:
    • Clear Outputs: Descriptive names for easier navigation as output 1, ​output 2 etc.
    • Quick Access: Home icon for fast back to start.
    • Easy Backtracking: Back arrow on all pages.


First Round High-Fi Wireframe Interview: Key Insights

  • A faster way to include the result in their main document instead of ​copying and pasting it manually.
  • Instead of displaying an error message, create a disabled generate ​button.


Add an introduction to the email assistant version 1

Second Round Interview Key Insights

  • Instead of a "copy" button, consider adding an "insert" button that ​allows users to quickly add their results to their main document.


  • Users requested that they could see more templates, adding a ​summarizing button.

outcome & learnings

  • Performed UX research and delivered UI design with prototype.


  • User research: Identified needs & pain points of non-native English speakers.
  • Iterative design: Refined user interface for ease of use & clarity.
  • User-friendly prototype: Enabled user testing & feedback.
  • AI-powered features: Introductions, conclusions, word choice improvements.
  • Non-native English speaker empowerment: Improved writing quality & efficiency.


  • During usability testing, I understand that It's important to consider the difference between ​what users say and what they actually do. This gap between intention and action can provide ​valuable insights for improving products and services.


  • I learned the importance of understanding the nuances of user behavior for creating successful ​and impactful products.



Case Study 4

How might we empower new cooks with clear, engaging, ​and comprehensive recipe instructions that build their ​confidence and skills?



PROJECT OVERVIEW

Savr Recipes App is a new startup that wants to make it easier for people to follow ​new recipes, and cook great meals.


The primary goal was to resolve the challenges of new cooks through clear and ​engaging recipe instructions.


Target users were individuals who had chosen a recipe and were in the kitchen, ready ​to start cooking and following the instructions.


As a UX Researcher and Designer for Savr Recipes App, I focused my research on the ​challenges users face while cooking, with the goal of creating a user-friendly interface.


We were given a few constraints:

  • Recipes are written as text, in ordered steps from start to finish.
  • The design should be designed as a feature for the Savr recipes native mobile app.

I conducted qualitative user research methods, I aim to


  • Help new cooks with step-by-step instructions.
  • Make cooking fun and easy by designing a user-friendly interface that addresses ​common struggles.


Research Setup

  1. Document Analysis

2. Competitive Analysis

  • I analyzed the user interviews that the client provided.


  • KEY TAKEAWAYS
    • Difficulty understanding complex recipes with many steps.
    • Feeling unprepared and stressed, especially with irreversible ​steps.
    • Inefficiency due to unclear instructions or lack of ​organization.
    • Difficulty learning and mastering new cooking techniques.
    • Frustration from mistakes leading to timing and flavor ​issues.


Competitive Analysis Chart: Yummly, Cookpad, Kitchen Stories


  • KEY TAKEAWAYS
    • Personalized Recommendations: Catered to user ​preferences for a curated experience.
    • Interactive Shopping List: Checkmarks offer intuitive ​progress tracking.
    • Informed Recipe Choices: User ratings and reviews ​build trust and confidence.
    • Visually Engaging & Informative: Step-by-step ​photos and cooking tips enhance user skill and ​understanding.
    • Simple & Efficient Design: Prioritizes ease of use and ​future built-in timer for improved time management.

Design process

Step 1: Ideation & Sketches

  • Based on the problem statement, target audience, design ​constraints, and research insights, here are some potential ​solutions for the Savr Recipes app:


Potential Solutions for Savr Recipes

Improving the User Experience for the Savr Recipes App with a Crazy Eight


  • Visual Recipe Timeline: See steps & estimate time for optimal ​planning.
  • Cooking Technique Library: Learn new skills & boost confidence in ​the kitchen.
  • Interactive Recipe Checklist: Stay organized & avoid mistakes for ​perfect results.
  • Equipment List & Preparation Tips: Be prepared & reduce stress ​during cooking.
  • Recipe Reviews with Photos: Get inspired & see what the dish ​should look like.

Design Process

Step 2: Low Fi Wireframe

Step 3: Design Inspiration and Style Guide

Savr Recipe Color Palette and Fonts

  • I created a mood ​board and style ​guides. These guides ​include fonts and ​colors that align with ​Savr Recipe key ​attributes, such as ​clear and concise and ​time saving

Low Fi Wire Wireframe of Savr Recipes

Savr Recipe Moodboard

Design Process

Step 4: High Fi Wireframe & Prototype

High Fi Wireframe of Savr Recipes

See: Savr Recipes Prototype

Design process

Step 4: High Fi Wireframe Interview Key Insights


  • After crafting a high-fidelity prototype with interactive elements, I conducted interviews with five participants to gather feedback.


  • KEY TAKEAWAYS
    • Easy to use & discover recipes.
    • Clear instructions & helpful features.
    • Visually appealing & organized.
    • Room for improvement:
      • Adjust recipe sizes.
      • Plan meals.
      • Shopping list integration.
      • Recipe scaling & conversion.


outcome & learnings

  • Performed UX research and delivered UI design with prototype in 7 days.


  • Outcomes
    • Positive User Experience: Savr Recipes met user expectations for recipe variety, clarity, user-​friendly features, and personalized recommendations.
    • Intuitive Design: Navigation, search, and saving functionality were praised for their ease of use.
    • Clear Instructions: Users found recipe instructions and ingredient lists easy to follow.
    • Visually Appealing: The recipe presentation and organization were well-received.


  • Learnings
    • Customization is desired: Users request features like serving size adjustment and recipe scaling ​for flexibility.
    • Planning & Management: Integrating meal planning and shopping list features would enhance ​convenience.
    • Continuous Improvement: User feedback is valuable for ongoing app development and feature ​prioritization.
    • Maximizing User Value: Implementing suggested features can further improve the app's ​usability, convenience, and overall user experience.


  • Savr Recipes has been well-received by users, proving its potential as a valuable cooking resource. ​Implementing suggested improvements would further enhance the user experience and contribute ​to the app's long-term success.
